          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="483" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834009?width=860&amp;height=483" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">碧桂园正迅速成为中国陷入困境的房地产市场最近一次低迷中最引人注目的受害者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Qilai Shen/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001127802"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cao-li" itemprop="url" rel="author">曹莉</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/frances-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">弗朗西斯·尹</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 7:39（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-company-country-garden-holdings-default-risk-22b3bd64"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国最大的幸存房地产开发商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/2007" class="">碧桂园控股</a>面临的问题越来越多<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司正拼命避免重蹈<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">许多违约竞争对手的</a>覆辙。</p><p>这家拥有 31 年历史的公司表示，预计将出现 16 年前上市以来最严重的亏损，并估计 2023 年上半年的赤字可能高达 76 亿美元。该开发商还表示，其合同7 月份销售额同比下降 60%，降幅比前几个月大得多。</p><p>周五更新后，碧桂园在香港上市的股价跌至历史新低。本来就处于深陷困境的美元债券也进一步下跌。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="980" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834008?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>该开发商曾在公寓年销售量上与行业巨头<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/EGRNF" class="company-name">中国恒大集团</a>竞争，但现在正迅速成为中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-housing-troubles-derail-a-developers-comeback-4786300?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">陷入困境的房地产市场</a>第二次衰退中最引人注目的受害者。</p><p>今年早些时候，中国取消了严格的 Covid-19 大流行限制，并且当局指导银行向包括碧桂园在内的选定开发商提供更多融资后，全国新房销量短暂上升。第二季度房地产市场下滑，而中国更广泛的经济复苏也失去了动力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834007?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>总部位于佛山的碧桂园表示，其利润率缩水，房地产项目价值缩水，公寓销售连续四个月下降，再融资变得更加困难。本周早些时候，碧桂园<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/country-garden-chinas-largest-surviving-developer-sinks-into-debt-crisis-2a525173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">未能支付其美元债券 2250 万美元的利息</a>。它有 30 天的宽限期来筹集资金。</p><p>该公司周四晚间表示，它一直在努力“采取一切手段进行自救”，并表示该公司正在经历该行业前所未有的极其困难的时期。</p><p> “跌倒了，就要爬起来。”碧桂园表示，正在不遗余力解决流动性问题，始终致力于为业主交付住房。该公司正在加快销售现金回收，控制支出，并削减了高级管理人员和其他员工的工资。其董事长兼控股股东杨惠妍及其家族已向该公司提供了相当于 49 亿美元的贷款和其他财务支持。</p><p>碧桂园违约将对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-has-slid-into-severe-depression-real-estate-giant-says-11661863259?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国房地产业</a>造成又一次重大打击，并有可能进一步损害中国购房者的信心。市场参与者表示，这也将消除投资者对房地产债务复苏的任何希望。</p><p>香港私募股权公司开元资本首席投资官布洛克·西尔弗斯表示：“市场现在基本上无法投资。” “系统性风险比之前预期的要大得多，”他补充道。</p><p>债券投资者此前认为，北京不会让碧桂园重蹈恒大的覆辙。恒大是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/evergrande-restructuring-is-a-warning-to-chinas-other-creditors-c5d17734?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球负债最重的房地产开发商</a>，多年来一直在积极扩张。碧桂园在繁荣时期在中国二三线城市建立了庞大的业务，但其债务并不像恒大集团那么多，恒大集团于 2021 年底拖欠了国际债务。</p><p>碧桂园此前曾被当局列为模范开发商，并能够发行有政府担保的国内债券。最近，它在该行业私营开发商中的地位似乎有所下降。</p><p>上周，中国央行召开了一次民营企业会议，其中包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/960" class="company-name">龙湖集团控股</a>等房地产开发商</p>和旭辉控股。与会者中并未列出碧桂园。<p></p><p>中国官方媒体周五报道称，中国证监会组织了一次与房地产开发商和金融机构的在线会议，试图了解他们面临的问题以及可能需要什么。</p><p>澳新银行高级中国策略师邢兆鹏表示，“房地产行业对经济的拖累预计将持续存在，目前开发商的下滑没有放缓的迹象。”</p><p>穆迪投资者服务公司周五表示，碧桂园规模庞大，意味着其信贷困境可能会蔓延到中国的房地产和金融市场，并延迟房地产行业的复苏。该信用评级公司指出，该开发商拥有约100亿美元的未偿还美元债券，并表示其财务问题可能会让购房者更加担心其他开发商的稳定性。</p><p>穆迪表示：“这些发展可能会在短期内将潜在购房者从私人开发商转向国有开发商（即使不是从房地产市场）。”他补充说，碧桂园在中国部分地区的房价上涨也可能面临压力。</p><p>写信给曹莉（ <a href="mailto:li.cao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">li.cao@wsj.com）</a>和弗朗西斯·尹（Frances Yoon）（ <a href="mailto:frances.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">frances.yoon@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 11:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-company-country-garden-holdings-default-risk-22b3bd64</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-company-country-garden-holdings-default-risk-22b3bd64<author><![CDATA[Cao LiFrances Yoon]]></author><category>华尔街日报亚洲财经</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>房地产服务/交易</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业融资</category><category>公司债务工具</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>高收益公司债券</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>债务/债券市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>碧桂园控股</category><category>2007.香港</category><category>香港:2007</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业融资</category><category>公司债务工具</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>高收益公司债券</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>债务</category><category>债券市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>房地产服务</category><category>交易</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Here’s What a $5 Million Retirement Looks Like in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>退休人员公开他们的财务生活以及他们如何度过时间和金钱<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832718/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>身着粉红色衣服的退休人员帕特·弗雷 (Pat Frey) 经常与朋友一起在大自然中散步。丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》<span>丽贝卡·斯坦普夫 (Rebecca Stumpf) 的《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122102"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">维罗妮卡·达格尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>多少钱都无法让退休后无忧无虑，但 500 万美元可能就差不多了。</p><p>很少有美国人能够在 401(k) 计划和个人退休账户中存下接近这一金额的钱。根据<a href="https://www.ebri.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">员工福利研究所</a>使用 2019 年消费者财务调查对退休账户进行的分析，500 万美元的退休储蓄金使您跻身前 0.1% 的家庭之列。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1092" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d663f044-8f28-4ec7-8377-2302a6c566d6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>为了了解 500 万美元可以在退休后购买什么，我们采访了全国各地拥有该金额储蓄的退休人员。</p><p>大多数人从未想过会成为百万富翁，但从职业生涯的早期就勤于储蓄。</p><p>尽管与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retirement-under-1-million-america-846a6ab6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">我们介绍的许多退休人员</a>相比，他们不太担心自己的钱花光了，但他们并不都过着奢侈的生活。有些人已经很多年没有买新衣服了。其他人继续兼职工作。</p><p>他们在环球旅行上挥霍无度，但像大多数年长的美国人一样，担心自己的健康和家人。</p><p>仅靠金钱也无法解决退休人员面临的另一个问题：如何在人生的这一章中找到目的和意义？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>保罗·谢姆韦尔 (Paul Shemwell) 在驾驶商用飞机和喷气式战斗机四十年后于 12 月退休。</p><p>尽管这位 65 岁的老人感觉自己的财务状况很安全，已经攒下了约 610 万美元，但他还没有制定接下来的飞行计划。</p><p>对于这位前飞行员来说，这种随意的态度是一个巨大的改变，他在空军的 13 年中磨练了自己的战略思维能力。他的服役经历也教会他仔细权衡自己的选择，这一理念指导着他的退休生活。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2decacce-5119-4fbc-9b6f-3b2bd857ad6d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LUV" class="">西南航空公司</a>工作 28 年后，他不再乘坐飞机<span class="company-name-type">，</span>但旅行仍然是他的热情所在。他计划今年秋天进行四次旅行，这种旅行癖让他每月花费约 3,000 美元。他每月还要花费大约 9,000 美元用于财产税、房屋和汽车保险等费用。</p><p>他的一天通常从锻炼或网球课开始。作为一名狂热的滑雪爱好者，他已经购买了本赛季的通行证，并计划每年至少进行一次水肺潜水旅行。</p><p>谢姆韦尔拒绝了几份重返驾驶舱的工作机会，部分原因是他不需要钱。</p><p>他计划在达到完全退休年龄后领取<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/social-security-payment-increase-cola-2024-retirement-a3fce38e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社会保障</a>，这将使年收入增加约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/173863f5-743a-4d58-a219-b57a7e01cbf8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>空巢老人的生活是另一个巨大的变化。他的儿子是大学二年级学生，女儿今年秋天开始上大学。谢姆韦尔已离婚并拥有共同监护权，他表示，他将深入参与孩子的生活作为首要任务。</p><p>他的航班时刻表使他能够灵活地参加孩子们的大部分网球和足球比赛。现在他们都在上学了，他想去看看他们比赛。</p><p>谢姆韦尔现在花更多的时间和他的朋友在一起，大多数工作日都会和他们一起吃午餐。</p><p>他不是一个活跃的交易者，但仍关注市场。他的投资组合<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/it-isnt-just-boomers-lots-of-older-americans-are-stock-obsessed-ca069e1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">95%是股票</a>，大部分是指数基金，还有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>等少数个股<span class="company-name-type">。</span> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832732?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">保罗·谢姆韦尔最近再次开始打网球。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的杰克·汤普森</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他的父亲已经 90 多岁了，所以谢姆韦尔并不担心他大量的股票配置。</p><p> “我的计划是继续量入为出或量入为出，保持投资并为我的孩子们留下一些东西，”他说。</p><p>谢姆韦尔在休斯顿的房屋抵押贷款还剩大约 30 万美元。他的再融资利率为 2.99%，因此他并不急于偿还债务。</p><p>他驾驶的是一辆 2016 款英菲尼迪，行驶里程约为 80,000 英里。这辆车以及他为女儿购买的二手奔驰都是付费的。他每月全额支付信用卡账单。</p><p> “我喜欢让事情变得简单，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-2.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Jay Myer 积累了足够的积蓄，可以在 2020 年提前退休，因为他在 401(k) 计划中缴纳了数十年的最高缴款。</p><p> 25 岁时，迈尔读了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vanguards-founder-a-force-of-nature-11547812685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">先锋创始人约翰·博格尔 (John Bogle)</a>写的一本支持低成本指数基金的书。他也按照著名选股家彼得·林奇的建议购买了个股，“买你所知道的”。对于现年 61 岁的迈尔来说，这意味着科技股和与他进行软件交易的公司的股票，其中包括家得<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HD" class="">宝 (Home Depot)</a> <span class="company-name-type">，</span>他在几十年前以每股 3 美元的分割调整价格购买了该公司。</p><p> “我当时还很年轻，才读到有关退休的文章，但这对我来说很有意义。如果你降低投资成本，你就会保留更多的利润，”迈尔说，他的退休账户投资于七只先锋指数基金。</p><p>他和 60 岁的妻子安妮塔 (Anita) 开着二手车，并严格遵守预算，以便 Myer 从 22 岁起就可以向他的 401(k) 账户缴纳最高年度限额。安妮塔 (Anita) 一直担任牙科保健员，直到 2000 年他们的第二个儿子出生。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d872ec8a-8e9f-4719-9763-3d49c3645f1b.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>迈尔说，他决定提前退休的部分原因是他的继父是一位小企业主，喜欢旅行和与孙辈共度时光。</p><p> “他向我展示了你可以放下工作场所并重新认识自己，”迈尔说。</p><p>起初，失去稳定的薪水是很可怕的。当 2020 年市场暴跌时，他仔细检查了这对夫妇的每一次购买，甚至餐巾纸，但很快意识到，考虑到他们的健康储蓄，这样做是没有必要的。</p><p>这对夫妇现在拥有 420 万美元，一半在退休账户，一半在应税账户。</p><p>这对夫妇利用最近出售亚特兰大房屋的收益，以 925,000 美元在卡里购买了一套房子，距离他们经常见到的大儿子的家人有 2 英里。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迈尔斯夫妇喜欢烹饪、园艺和旅行，并计划改进他们的新家。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Kate Medley</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他们每年花费约 130,000 美元，其中包括 5,000 美元的财产税。他们每个月在食品上花费约 700 美元，在健康保险上花费 1,000 美元。 （由于他们目前用现金储备支出，这对夫妇的应税收入足够低，有资格获得保险补贴。）</p><p>为了最大化他每月的福利，迈尔表示他会等到 70 岁才领取社会保障。</p><p>这对夫妇曾考虑出售一些个股，以将更多资金投入债券，但由于利润所欠的资本利得税而打消了念头。他们决定把最大的赢家留给他们的两个儿子。</p><p>迈尔斯夫妇每年的旅行预算约为 20,000 美元，他们正计划今年去西班牙旅行，他们的小儿子今年就住在那里。</p><p>两人都喜欢烹饪和园艺。迈尔说他很享受自由自在的时间。</p><p> “现在我有了更多的时间，我学会了拥抱无聊，放慢脚步，有时接受读书或骑自行车就足够了，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>对于胡亨利博士来说，工作是实现令人满意的退休生活的一部分。</p><p>这位加利福尼亚州欧文市的外科医生过去每周工作长达 80 个小时，但现在他在假期期间兼职工作。 “我真的很喜欢旅行，”72 岁的胡说。</p><p> Hwu 是一名来自台湾的移民，他说他和已故的妻子于 1979 年来到美国。在芝加哥学习了五年外科手术并于 1986 年在密歇根州完成结直肠外科奖学金后，Hwu 搬到了南加州，他和妻子在那里抚养了三个孩子。</p><p>在达到医疗实践规定的 65 岁强制退休年龄之前，Hwu 开始阅读有关退休的书籍（他说还有《华尔街日报》的文章）。他开始打高尔夫球和泡菜球，还买了一把吉他，重拾了自医学院以来他几乎没有时间从事的一项爱好。</p><p>但 2016 年退休后，他错过了工作并开始接受以前诊所的任务。</p><p>每天早上，他都会问自己这一天要做什么。 “我不喜欢那种感觉，”胡说，他的妻子在他退休后不久就去世了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832859?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Henry Hwu 博士于 2016 年正式退休，但在不旅行时继续兼职工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ryan Young</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>胡每年旅行长达三个月，去台湾看望他 98 岁的母亲，或者游览苏格兰、法国、德国、日本和瑞士，他曾在那里给朋友买了很多巧克力，结果行李箱都坏了。</p><p> Hwu经常带着他的吉他。最近在伦敦时，他给了一位街头音乐家 20 英镑让他让位，以便他可以演奏 Everly Brothers 的《Let It Be Me》。 “我不知道人们是否喜欢它，但有一位观众站在我面前，”胡说。</p><p>胡仍然喜欢参加医学会议和阅读医学期刊。</p><p>在 2017 年的一次会议上，他遇到了洛斯阿拉莫斯一家乡村医院唯一的外科医生 NM Hwu，现在大多数月份都会前往洛斯阿拉莫斯为外科医生接班几天。在那里，他喜欢徒步旅行并拜访在阿尔伯克基担任会计师的儿子。</p><p>在家时，Hwu 会去上吉他课，并经常见到他的女儿和小孙女。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f3b9dd2c-d95e-4677-81b1-f14a149509ca.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>他的房子价值150万美元。他拥有第二套房子，价值 120 万美元，每月租金为 3,500 美元。他每套房子欠约 50 万美元，但并不急于偿还抵押贷款，因为利率低于 3%。</p><p> Hwu 将其退休账户中超过 100 万美元的资金几乎全部投资于股票基金和个股，包括苹果、<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">英伟达</a><span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>他每月领取 2,700 美元的社会保障福利，从 65 岁开始领取。他每年领取约 13 万美元的养老金，去年从每日工作中赚取约 30 万美元。</p><p>旅行是他的大手笔，每年花费 10 万美元。其他开支约为每月 4,000 美元，这还不包括他的抵押贷款付款。</p><p>他每年还支付 6,800 美元的长期护理保险。</p><p> “我妈妈活到了 98 岁，我有一天会无法照顾自己，”他说。 “我想减轻孩子们的负担。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/archibald/1JhIu4HsU3kUrK8q6t8nArRD6-qm34M9iySjy14qk7vc-chapter-4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>在成长过程中，鲍勃·弗雷（Bob Frey）从未想过自己会成为百万富翁退休。</p><p>从西点军校毕业后，他在现役期间获得了硕士学位，然后通过陆军预备役奖学金和退伍军人法案获得了兽医学位。他担任预备役军官 26 年，60 岁退休。他从 30 多岁开始就用尽了退休计划缴款。</p><p>日子有时很艰难，比如当他借了大约 15 万美元开办兽医诊所时。多年来，他卖掉了三项业务，其中包括两家兽医诊所。他说，这些退出极大地增加了他的价值。</p><p>如今，80 岁的鲍勃和 75 岁的妻子帕特·弗雷已经存下了约 610 万美元，其中几乎一半投资于个人退休账户。</p><p>弗雷每年领取 60,000 美元的军事养老金，加上每年约 14,000 美元的退伍军人伤残补偿金，因为他在越南服役后出现了听力损失。这对夫妇从社会保障金中总共领取了约 56,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b82deef5-2fa7-4359-8b0c-802cb8012644.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “我们拥有的钱比我们一生花的还要多，”他说。</p><p>这对夫妇结婚已有 30 多年，育有 5 个成年子女。 20 世纪 90 年代初，他们搬到了蒙大拿州博兹曼，寻求新的开始并更接近大自然。帕特继续她的护理生涯，鲍勃接受重新培训，成为一名认证财务规划师。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您为退休制定了哪些财务计划？请通过下面的表格告诉我们您的经历。</em></p></div></div><p>弗雷家族尽管富有，但通常都会避免其装饰。鲍勃说他已经大约 20 年没有买过新的运动外套了。这对夫妇住在蒙大拿州，他们说他们不太用得着正装，宁愿穿着牛仔裤和运动鞋到处走动。帕特经常和朋友一起去大自然散步。</p><p>弗雷夫妇预计将花费约 150 万美元来帮助支付他们九个孙辈的教育费用。他们每年还向他们最喜欢的慈善机构（包括他们的教堂）捐赠大约 40,000 美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832798?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">鲍勃·弗雷 (Bob Frey) 在世界各地和离家不远的加拉廷河 (Gallatin River) 飞钓。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rebecca Stumpf for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这对夫妇没有债务，也没有过多调整他们的投资，其中大约 70% 投资于股票基金。鲍勃说，他们死后可能会向慈善机构留下约 100 万美元。</p><p>弗雷夫妇也很重视旅行，每年会拨出约 35,000 美元用于环游世界。他们曾五次访问新西兰，鲍勃经常将他对飞钓的热爱与阿拉斯加、墨西哥和南美洲的旅行结合起来。</p><p>他们还喜欢与朋友单独旅行。帕特经常与朋友一起前往欧洲和加拉帕戈斯群岛。她跳过了鲍勃的狩猎之旅。</p><p> “我不想睡在帐篷里，把麋鹿带出树林，”她说。</p><p>写信给 Veronica Dagher <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com）</a>和 Anne Tergesen（ <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com）</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/2d22c5e9-a490-4c14-9b85-792395763a6e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/89ceea19-a743-45d2-8530-c974dc040b2e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/heres-what-a-5-million-retirement-looks-like-in-america-1abc76d9<author><![CDATA[Veronica DagherAnne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>老年健康</category><category>人口健康</category><category>健康</category><category>个人退休账户</category><category>个人财务</category><category>退休计划</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Aims to Restore Prestige in Race to Moon’s South Pole]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>成功可能标志着莫斯科有能力克服制裁并展示其技术实力，但挑战是严峻的<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833990/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="搭载 Luna-25 着陆器的联盟号火箭在俄罗斯东方航天发射场发射。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>搭载 Luna-25 着陆器的联盟号火箭在俄罗斯东方航天发射场发射升空。讲义/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>讲义/法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124483"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124483"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-m-simmons" itemprop="url" rel="author">安·M·西蒙斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 11 日上午 5:11（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-aims-to-restore-prestige-in-race-to-moons-south-pole-86c25170"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>周五，俄罗斯发射了近 50 年来的首个月球着陆器，试图成为第一个到达月球南极的国家，对于一个急于证明自己仍然拥有适合伟大世界的技术能力的国家来说，这是一个象征性时刻力量。</p><p>从成功发射到 8 月 21 日探测器在极地崎岖的地形上着陆，困难是多方面的。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-sanctioned-russias-billionaires-now-they-are-fighting-back-836ee65?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方</a>因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰战争</a>而实施的制裁意味着莫斯科的合作者比过去少了。俄罗斯科学家也在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-rockets-into-the-global-space-race-4553f159?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与印度的类似任务</a>展开竞争，并希望首先让自己的探测器着陆。据俄罗斯国际文传电讯社报道，俄罗斯航天局局长尤里·鲍里索夫在发射后对东方航天发射场的工作人员表示：“我们现在将等待 21 日。” “我希望能够在月球上实现高精度软着陆。”</p><p>除了提升俄罗斯的威望之外，首次登陆极地可能是向前迈出的宝贵一步，有助于科学家进一步了解那里是否有足够数量的冰来提供燃料、氧气和饮用水，以支持人类在极地可能的定居。未来。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C795F96F-6138-433C-9F77-B324D230F23C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussia-aims-to-restore-prestige-in-race-to-moons-south-pole-86c25170&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">俄罗斯周五发射了近 50 年来首次登月飞船，力图成为第一个到达月球南极的国家。尽管受到西方制裁，这一成功可能标志着莫斯科的技术实力。照片：Sergei Savostyanov/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Luna-25 着陆器从距离俄罗斯远东莫斯科约 3,450 英里的东方航天发射场发射，标志着该国自 1976 年以来首次执行月球任务，同时也正值新一波国家扩大其太空足迹之际。</p><p>印度的月船三号（Chandrayaan-3）是一艘搭载轨道飞行器、着陆器和月球车的航天器，预计将于本月晚些时候降落在月球南极。今年五月，中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-launches-three-astronauts-including-first-civilian-into-orbit-898a29b9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将第一位民用宇航员送入轨道</a>，作为空间站新船员的一部分。</p><p>美国国家航空航天局 (NASA) 计划<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nasa-canadian-space-agency-select-astronauts-for-artemis-moon-mission-fb0a4b49?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">于 2024 年底进行载人绕月飞行，</a>这将是数十年来首次将人类带入太空深处，并为该机构希望与月球进行的着陆奠定基础。 2025 年，美国航天器制造商 SpaceX。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832312?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Luna-25 预计将在一年内收集月球表面的读数。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：roscosmos/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832317?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Luna-25 将由从东方航天发射场发射的联盟号火箭送上月球。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：俄罗斯航天局/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于俄罗斯和俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>来说，Luna-25 任务的风险尤其高。乌克兰战争以来实施的制裁使其与美国和欧洲国家的大部分合作停止，阻碍了多项任务，并在北京扩大其太空野心之际，促使俄罗斯与中国走得更近。</p><p>宾夕法尼亚大学物理与天文学系高级研究员本杰明·L·施密特在书面评论中表示：“我们现在可能正在见证美国和俄罗斯联邦在太空领域重要合作的最后篇章。”</p><p> “科学界和宇航员界的情绪已经开始转向实现这样一个未来：由于普京政权在乌克兰的可怕行为以及俄罗斯对更广泛的全球民主国家的混合威胁，美国宇航局和俄罗斯航天局不再是密切的合作伙伴，”他说。</p><p>美国宇航局和俄罗斯航天局继续在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-russia-agree-to-use-russian-ship-for-backup-space-station-mission-11673703125?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国际空间站</a>的载人发射和运营方面开展合作。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/790bf497-ab57-43ce-b23d-0599c0e07e39.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>印度和其他二十多个国家已同意美国支持的太空探索原则，而俄罗斯正在与中国合作建立国际月球研究站，计划到 2036 年在月球上建立基地。自 2011 年以来，中国已被排除在外与 NASA 合作受美国法律约束。</p><p>普京铭记俄罗斯对其苏联时期的太空探索历史感到自豪，因此坚称莫斯科将继续发展其月球计划，尽管西方制裁。</p><p>去年入侵后不久，他在访问东方航天发射场时表示：“尽管外界有任何困难和企图阻碍我们的前进，我们仍以祖先的愿望为指导，继续前进。”</p><p> Roscosmos said the 1,764-pound, four-legged Luna-25 is expected to gather readings on the lunar surface for a year. According to Roscosmos, it is equipped with a 1.6-meter-long Lunar Robotic Arm, to remove and collect surface deposits, and several scientific instruments, including for the study of plasma and dust components of the lunar polar exosphere.</p><p> “The south pole is strategic because of its rich water-ice resources and long-term potential as a site for mining, industry, and settlement,” Namrata Goswami, an independent scholar on space policy, said in an email. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="888" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832316?width=1260&amp;height=888" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Russian President Vladimir Putin said Moscow will continue to develop its lunar program despite Western sanctions.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: mikhail klimentyev/kremlin/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832744?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Chang&#39;e 5 lunar mission lifts off at the Wenchang Space Launch Center in Hainan Province, China.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mark Schiefelbein/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A successful mission would “demonstrate that Russian space effort remains a major capability for the country,” she added. “That&#39;s the message Putin will have sent to the rest of the world. It is an important signal not only to the West but to China,” which the Kremlin has been courting to join future space missions.</p><p> A positive outcome is also important to Russia for allaying doubts about its military superiority over Ukraine after numerous battlefield setbacks exposed technical and strategic flaws, according to analysts who cover the role of the space industry in Russian politics.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Should Russia continue to plow resources into its space program? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> In recent years, launch malfunctions, construction accidents, corruption scandals and a dearth of expertise have compounded what observers have described as a deepening crisis in Russia&#39;s space industry. Western sanctions, among them technology export controls and restrictions aimed at degrading Russia&#39;s aerospace and space sectors, have exacerbated the challenges to Russia&#39;s space program.</p><p> “At a minimum, a successful Luna-25 mission could result in a chance for the Putin regime to engage in its usual propaganda aimed at playing down the effect of sanctions on its high-tech aerospace sector,” said Schmitt, a co-founder of Duke University&#39;s Space Diplomacy Lab. “Conversely, a high-profile mission failure might suggest that technology export controls may indeed be having their intended impact.”</p><p> Pavel Luzin, a nonresident senior fellow at the Washington-based Center for European Policy Analysis, a public policy institution where his focus includes Russia&#39;s space policy, said it would be impossible for Russia to develop its space capabilities “when it is self-isolated from other countries and people in the world because of its aggressive and criminal behavior.”</p><p> Russia&#39;s Luna-25, Luna-26 and Luna-27 probes all depend on European electronics and equipment, Luzin said, adding that “even if Russia purchased all necessary things years before 2022, it would be hard for Roscosmos to use them without partnering ties.”</p><p> The mission to the moon&#39;s south pole is exceptionally difficult. Russian space engineers have never carried out such a mission. Nor had the Vostochny Cosmodrome ever hosted a comparable launch. Local authorities ordered nearby villagers to evacuate to avoid the risk of being struck by the rocket&#39;s boosters when they separate from the main vehicle.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The craggy lunar terrain also complicates prospects for a successful landing. Since the end of the Cold War, India, Israel and Japan have all attempted and failed to successfully land on the lunar south pole, “showing how difficult this is even for advanced spacefaring nations,” Goswami said.</p><p> Roscosmos officials have acknowledged the dangers of the mission, with the agency&#39;s head, Yuri Borisov, telling Putin in June that “such missions are always risky.” He estimated the probability of success at 70%.</p><p> NASA Administrator Bill Nelson told reporters Tuesday that the US agency wished the Russians well in their Luna-25 mission, but poured cold water on any future Russian attempt to land cosmonauts on the moon soon.</p><p> “I think the space race is really between us and China,” he said.</p><p> Still, excitement in Russia has been building for days. Many people brim with pride over being the first nation to send a human into space. Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin, who stunned Americans by circling the Earth in 1961, remains a national hero whose story is taught to Russian schoolchildren.</p><p> State media has published detailed dossiers of the lunar lander and television commentators have gone into overdrive extolling Russia&#39;s competence in the space arena. The event is expected to receive wall-to-wall live coverage.</p><p> The risks if it goes wrong, are high, though.</p><p> Said Goswami, the space analyst: “It&#39;s Russia&#39;s game to lose.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832765?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Visitors stand in front of a Vostok spacecraft at an exhibition in Moscow. The Vostok 1 carried Yuri Gagarin into space.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: maxim shipenkov/European Pressphoto Agency</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Micah Maidenberg contributed to this article</em> .</p><p> Write to Ann M. Simmons at <a href="mailto:ann.simmons@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ann.simmons@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 09:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-aims-to-restore-prestige-in-race-to-moons-south-pole-86c25170</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-aims-to-restore-prestige-in-race-to-moons-south-pole-86c25170<author><![CDATA[Ann M. Simmons]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Astronomy</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>Space</category><category> Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category>贸易</category><category>external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>astronomy</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>政治</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>space</category><category> trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e industry news filter </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Wildfires Leave at Least 55 Dead on Hawaii’s Maui]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>飓风引发的大火摧毁了历史名镇拉海纳<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1E4C7220-8609-4F03-A17C-70F3E330A2CD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Satellite images showed the scale of destruction in the popular tourist town of Lahaina, Hawaii. Photo: Patrick T. Fallon/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124181"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alicia-caldwell" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alicia A. Caldwell</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/suryatapa-bhattacharya" itemprop="url" rel="author">Suryatapa Bhattacharya</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christine-mai-duc" itemprop="url" rel="author">Christine Mai-Duc</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 4:28 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> MAUI, Hawaii—Travis Miller was pulling into a grocery store in the town of Lahaina on Tuesday when a gust knocked over power lines and toppled trees onto parked cars. Soon he saw smoke and people running down the street, including a woman with burns on her feet, begging for help.</p><p> After dropping her off at an aid center, he rushed to his nearby home, where he heard propane tanks exploding and saw a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-maui-wildfires-hawaii-devastating-84651f12?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fast-moving blaze</a> approaching.</p><p> “I did not know a fire could be that big,” said the 37-year-old photographer, whose home burned down. “It was just tornadoes of fire going up in the air.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833903?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Water is dropped by helicopter on wildfires tearing through the Hawaiian island of Maui.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: US ARMY NATIONAL GUARD/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At least 55 people have been killed by the wildfire that destroyed much of Lahaina, the historic former capital of the Hawaiian Kingdom and a popular tourist destination, officials said.</p><p> That number is expected to rise in the coming days. Officials said they don&#39;t know how many people are missing, but it could be around 1,000. Search-and-rescue efforts are under way.</p><p> The Lahaina blaze is one of three that have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-wildfires-maui-big-island-lahaina-hurricane-dora-evacuations-800bf315?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">torn through Maui</a> this week, fueled by powerful winds caused by Hurricane Dora spinning hundreds of miles away. None of the fires were fully contained by late Thursday.</p><p> Gov. Josh Green called it the worst natural disaster in Hawaii history and said it would take years and billions of dollars to rebuild. President Biden has declared a major disaster in the state.</p><p> Videos and images from Lahaina show buildings, palm trees and cars engulfed in flames, while wind-whipped walls of fire and smoke spread. By Thursday, there was little more than smoldering rubble where surf shops, restaurants and homes once stood in the town of 12,000.</p><p> A massive, 150-year-old banyan tree that is a central feature of Lahaina&#39;s downtown was also damaged in the fire, which officials said was 80% contained Thursday afternoon.</p><p> “When you see the full extent of the destruction of Lahaina it will shock you,” Green said at a press conference Thursday.</p><p> He said some 1,000 structures have been destroyed and his administration is looking for 2,000 rooms in hotels and homes to temporarily house displaced people.</p><p> Another fire in the coastal town of Pulehu was 70% contained. A third fire, in the island&#39;s rural Upcountry, was still being assessed, but authorities said earlier that at least 1,000 acres burned in the area, home to Haleakala National Park. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833904?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A 150-year-old banyan tree was damaged in the fire that devastated downtown Lahaina.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: MARCO GARCIA/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Officials haven&#39;t determined the causes of the Maui wildfires, which started Tuesday and Wednesday.</p><p> They said they hadn&#39;t anticipated how quickly the Lahaina fire ended up moving into populated areas and that the rapid damage it caused made communications among emergency responders impossible at times.</p><p> Local residents said the Lahaina blaze didn&#39;t seem serious at first, until winds as fast as 60 miles an hour spread it out of control.</p><p> “Within just two or three hours, the majority of the town was gone,” said Richard Coennen, a 37-year-old project manager for a construction company.</p><p> Bosco Bae, a 39 year-old art gallery employee, said, “It was very apocalyptic…I couldn&#39;t see a thing, but it was like raining fire, embers raining down.”</p><p> Residents reported running into the water to escape the flames. The Coast Guard said it rescued 14 people from the ocean.</p><p> Eddy Garcia was working on his farm outside Lahaina when powerful winds started sweeping through his property, eventually causing the first tornado he had ever seen.</p><p> “It 100% devastated all my structures—lifted up things and threw them in the air, and busted all the power lines in this small area,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1090" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b962de2e-47c2-43e9-bada-09e646fc6ee9-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> When he ventured into the town of Lahaina, he saw devastation everywhere.</p><p> “Everything is burnt to concrete frames. There&#39;s nothing left,” said Garcia. “If their house is gone, it&#39;s gone. Like all the way to the frame. There&#39;s nothing for them to collect.”</p><p> Garcia said he plans to kill a few pigs from his farm to help feed the community in the coming days.</p><p> Some 11,000 people were without power across the western of Maui, according to the Federal Emergency Management Agency, and cellphone and landline service had been knocked out.</p><p> The fires will likely be devastating to Maui&#39;s tourism industry. Nearly 1.5 million people visited the island in the first half of the year, up 5.7% from the same period in 2022, according to the state&#39;s Department of Business, Economic Development and Tourism.同期游客总支出为 34.7 亿美元，比去年增长约 25%。</p><p> AccuWeather estimated that the wildfires will cause $8 billion to $10 billion of damage and economic loss to Hawaii. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833907?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Burned-out cars were part of the trail of destruction left by the wildfire in Lahaina, Hawaii.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tiffany Kidder Winn/AP </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833905?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Residents carrying their belongings in suitcases after a wildfire swept through Lahaina.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ku&#39;u Kauanoe/Civil Beat/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> FEMA 表示，截至周四上午，毛伊岛的 6 个避难所已容纳 2000 多人。</p><p> Cecilia Paredes-Sunshine was on the second week of a vacation with her husband and three children in Maui when she saw billowing smoke and flames from her hotel located just north of Lahaina.</p><p> “You could see the black smoke all night,” the 47 year-old from Newport Beach, Calif., said.</p><p> With many roads closed, her family made their way through long, twisty back roads lined by burned trees to the town of Kahului. All of the local hotels were booked, so they rented a pair of sport-utility vehicles with roof-mounted tents and spent the night Wednesday in the parking lot of Maui High School, a shelter where other evacuees slept on mats on the floor. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="640" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/0e1c440f-9468-472b-9b4b-a40a24b48f11-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> President Biden addressed the disaster before a planned speech on veterans&#39; healthcare in Utah on Thursday. “Our prayers are with the people of Hawaii, but not just our prayers,” he said. “Every asset we have will be available.”</p><p>今年夏天，野火和其他形式的极端天气席卷了世界多个地区。大火席卷了希腊、葡萄牙和加拿大，而中国则面临着严重的洪水和灼热的热浪。 July was the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-2023-hottest-month-record-climate-change-5e5b3097?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">world&#39;s hottest month on record</a> .</p><p> “Climate change is here and it&#39;s affecting the islands and I think that&#39;s what you&#39;re seeing in this fire,” Green, the Hawaii governor, said.</p><p> Lahaina, which according to the local travel industry attracts about 80% of the tourists who visit Maui each year, is on the National Register of Historic Places. Hailama Farden, former president of the Hawaiian Historical Society, rode a tram through Lahaina as a child and learned about the groves of coconut trees, as well as the churches, temples and graveyards.</p><p> He had planned to take his 7-year-old daughter to Lahaina this weekend to show her the buildings where her great-grandparents and other relatives lived.</p><p> “I live vicariously through the stories of my grandfolks,” said Farden, 52. “I mourn the footsteps of my elders. I mourn for the culture that was.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833899?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An aerial image taken Thursday shows homes and other buildings burned to the ground in Lahaina, Hawaii.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·T.法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine">—Jennifer Calfas, Erin Ailworth, Allison Pohle, Ethan M. Steinberg, Michael Wright and Annie Linskey contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Alicia A. Caldwell at <a href="mailto:alicia.caldwell@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alicia.caldwell@wsj.com</a> , Suryatapa Bhattacharya at <a href="mailto:Suryatapa.Bhattacharya@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Suryatapa.Bhattacharya@wsj.com</a> and Christine Mai-Duc at <a href="mailto:christine.maiduc@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christine.maiduc@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 08:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hawaii-maui-wildfires-36-dead-6e07f2b7<author><![CDATA[Alicia A. CaldwellSuryatapa BhattacharyaChristine Mai-Duc]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category> wildfires</category><category> wsj-usnews</category><category> Wildfires</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>Natural Disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>disasters</category><category> accidents</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>natural disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>weather </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine’s Sea Drones Alter Balance of Power in Black Sea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Kyiv has used the unmanned vessels to strike back at Russia&#39;s more powerful navy <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.9493177387914" alt="An image from a sea drone showing a ship near the port of Novorossiysk, Russia. The unmanned vessels are no larger than a small fishing boat and have a range of up to 500 miles." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> An image from a sea drone showing a ship near the port of Novorossiysk, Russia. The unmanned vessels are no larger than a small fishing boat and have a range of up to 500 miles. REUTERS <span>REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124402"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124402"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jared Malsin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 11, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> ISTANBUL—Ukraine has altered the military balance of power in the Black Sea in recent months, using sea drones to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukrainian-military-warns-ships-against-heading-to-russian-black-sea-ports-b309e287?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strike back at Russia&#39;s more powerful navy</a> and threaten Russian military supply lines and shipping lanes.</p><p> Small, inexpensive and difficult to defend against, the homemade drones have allowed Ukraine to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukrainian-naval-drones-attack-russian-black-sea-port-81b4f2e6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">open up a new front in the war</a> , attacking strategic military targets and symbols of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-threats-to-shipping-bring-risk-of-war-to-black-sea-247cbf3a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Russia&#39;s dominance in the Black Sea</a> —including the headquarters of Moscow&#39;s fleet in occupied Crimea and a bridge connecting the peninsula to Russia. Ukraine says the drones are developed and produced domestically, but has been secretive about the details of the program.</p><p> The strikes <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-offers-plan-to-bypass-russias-black-sea-blockade-fcac8ef?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have intensified in recent days</a> as Ukraine has retaliated against a wave of Russian missile and drone strikes on Ukrainian ports on the Black Sea and threats to attack civilian ships heading to Ukraine. Russia also <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">withdrew in July</a> from an international agreement that allowed Ukraine to resume its Black Sea grain exports last year, imperiling a key link in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-creates-worst-global-food-crisis-since-2008-imf-says-11664553601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the global food-supply chain</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F461056A-8654-4C46-8FE3-867860EC96B9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">俄罗斯官方媒体周六报道，一架乌克兰海军无人机在克里米亚附近的刻赤海峡击中了一艘俄罗斯油轮。照片：乌克兰军方来自 Storyful<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Since Russia exited the agreement, Ukrainian sea drones have demonstrated their ability to strike across a swath of the Black Sea, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukrainian-naval-drones-attack-russian-black-sea-port-81b4f2e6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ramming a Russian landing ship</a> in a navy shipyard in the port city of Novorossiysk, more than 360 miles from Odesa, and an oil tanker that carried jet fuel for Moscow&#39;s armed forces. Earlier in July, Moscow also said a Ukrainian drone struck a Russian reconnaissance ship in the middle of the Black Sea.</p><p> Military analysts say the surface drones could change the complexion of the war by forcing Russia to commit more resources to protecting its ports, warships and cargo ships that it uses to transport weapons, fuel and other supplies for its military. The attacks are also expected to further raise shipping and insurance costs for vessels headed to Russia&#39;s vital Black Sea ports. In concert with recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-intensifies-drone-attacks-on-russia-moscow-says-f0ff7026?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">aerial drone attacks that have hit Moscow</a> , the drones show Kyiv&#39;s ability to strike far beyond the theater of war inside Ukraine. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="708" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832517?width=1260&amp;height=708" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A grain warehouse that was destroyed by a Russian drone strike on Ukraine&#39;s grain-exporting port of Odesa.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ukrainian Ground Forces/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="791" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832558?width=1260&amp;height=791" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Russian Navy patrols the waters near the Kerch Bridge, which connects Russia to the occupied Crimean Peninsula.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ALEXEY PAVLISHAK/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “I think the message is to say nothing is safe,” said Gabriela Iveliz Rosa Hernández, a research associate with the Arms Control Association who studies Eastern European militaries. “It&#39;s Ukraine reminding Russia that there is no normality.”</p><p> Ukraine isn&#39;t making much progress with a counteroffensive launched earlier this summer aimed at reclaiming land occupied by Russia earlier in the war. The operation is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">proceeding more slowly than expected</a> as Ukrainian forces run into heavily fortified Russian positions and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffensive-hunting-for-mines-78197558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">miles upon miles of minefields</a> . Air- and sea-drone attacks behind Russian lines have allowed Ukraine to open up new fronts in the war while the fighting moves slowly on the main battlefields. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="476" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/07b9551c-6f91-4523-b9dc-7a970a87f8ca-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The sea drones, also known as unmanned surface vehicles, are only 18 feet long—no larger than a small fishing boat—with a range of up to 800 kilometers, or about 500 miles, and can operate for up to 60 hours at a time, according to the Ukrainian government. Each vessel costs a quarter of a million dollars, a fraction of the tens, if not hundreds, of millions of dollars it costs to build the larger Russian ships that have been targeted by the drones.</p><p> The vessels&#39; small size makes them difficult to defend against in much the same way that aerial drones pose a challenge for air defenses: They are hard to detect. Once the small drones approach a larger ship, the steep angles involved in shooting at the vessels pose a challenge, experts say.</p><p> “A small vessel that has relatively little profile is hard to hit. If there are a number of them in some kind of a swarm, that makes it that much harder,” said Scott Savitz, a senior engineer at the Rand Corp., a US-government funded think tank, who has written studies on uncrewed vessels. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="671" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832591?width=1260&amp;height=671" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Turkey&#39;s Bayraktar TB-2 drones were instrumental in Ukraine&#39;s early resistance to the Russian invasion.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: petras malukas/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832580?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Ukrainian soldier watches footage from a drone. The vessels show Kyiv&#39;s ability to strike far beyond the theater of war inside Ukraine.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Libkos/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “What we&#39;re seeing is Ukraine instituting partial sea denial,” he said, referring to Ukraine&#39;s aim to limit the Russian navy&#39;s range of operations in the Black Sea.</p><p> For Ukraine, the drone attacks are the latest in a series of moves that have cut down the firepower of the Russian Black Sea fleet and derailed a possibly key element of Moscow&#39;s plans for the invasion. Earlier in the war, Ukraine used antiship missiles, aerial drones and sea mines to push back a possible Russian landing force from the area around Odesa. Those same weapons helped it reclaim the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-tiny-snake-island-plays-an-outsize-role-in-the-war-11656162000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">small but strategic Snake Island</a> in the Black Sea near the mouth of the Danube River and sink the flagship of the Russian fleet, the missile cruiser Moskva.</p><p> The so-called “mosquito fleet” of Ukrainian-made drones is the result of a wartime effort by Ukraine to build up its own naval forces, which were devastated when Russia seized Crimea and by the recent invasion. Though the Russian Black Sea fleet has been based in Crimea for more than two centuries, Ukraine received only one-fifth of the fleet&#39;s ships during the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991. It lost 80% of those when Russia occupied Crimea in 2014. Ukraine was forced to scuttle its flagship in the port city of Mykolaiv in March last year to prevent it from falling into Russian hands. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="709" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832561?width=1260&amp;height=709" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A still image from a video shows what it said was a Ukrainian drone attacking the Russian warship Priazovye in the Black Sea.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: RUSSIAN DEFENSE MINISTRY/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="709" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832565?width=1260&amp;height=709" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An image from a video released by Russia&#39;s Defense Ministry shows gunfire toward what it said was a Ukrainian sea drone attacking a Russian warship in June.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: RUSSIAN DEFENSE MINISTRY/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Dozens of countries have manufactured armed and unarmed sea drones for years, but the Ukraine war is the first time they have been used at such a large scale. Yemen&#39;s Houthi rebels have carried out a series of attacks using apparent uncrewed vessels in recent years, analysts say, killing two sailors on a Saudi warship in 2017.</p><p> In October, Ukraine used sea drones to attack the headquarters of the Russian Black Sea fleet in Sevastopol in Crimea. The attack, using a swarm of several drones, damaged a Russian minesweeper, according to Moscow&#39;s Ministry of Defense. Days later, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky announced a fundraising drive to build up a fleet of the uncrewed vessels. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1870" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/98cd0d4b-c843-4708-979f-1be0b9c7bdde-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The attacks have shown the potential to affect Russia&#39;s economy, which increasingly relies on its Black Sea ports for exports of oil, grain and other commodities. Data from Lloyd&#39;s List Intelligence showed that a drone attack on the Crimean bridge in July severely reduced the number of visits by ships to the Sea of Azov, just north of the bridge. Port calls fell by more than half in Novorossiysk following an attack on the port in November.</p><p> The Ukrainian government rarely comments on the drone attacks. Following the attack that rammed a Russian oil tanker working for the Kremlin&#39;s military over the weekend, Zelensky mentioned what he said were the “fair results” of work by Ukraine&#39;s defense industry.</p><p> “He, who brings problems to others, must feel what problems are,” he said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>To what extent will drones change modern-day warfare and military tactics? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> The Ukrainian government recently unveiled a new drone called the Magura 5. A model of the vessel was put on display at a defense expo in Istanbul in July. Turkey is also a world leader in drone manufacturing and its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-leans-on-armed-drones-western-missiles-to-thwart-russian-invasion-11646343771?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Bayraktar TB-2 drones</a> were instrumental in Ukraine&#39;s early resistance to the Russian invasion.</p><p> Turkish, Western and United Nations diplomats say they are working to bring Russia back into the Black Sea grain initiative, which would calm tensions in the region and allow some civilian shipping to resume to Ukraine&#39;s major Black Sea ports. In the absence of an agreement, uncrewed drones have given Ukraine the ability to push back on Russian attacks on its ports.</p><p> “The purpose of such operations is to destroy Russia&#39;s military capabilities in the Black Sea, and in the future to restore freedom of maritime navigation in the Black Sea,” said Olya Korbut, a researcher with the Center for European Policy Analysis in Washington and the Institute for Black Sea Strategic Studies in Kyiv. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832617?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An oil depot in Sevastopol, in Russian-occupied Crimea, was struck in April in what Russian officials said was a Ukrainian drone attack.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TASS/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Jared Malsin at <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee<author><![CDATA[Jared Malsin]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category> Marine Transport</category><category>港口/港口运营</category><category>Aerospace/Defense</category><category>货运/物流</category><category>Industrial Goods</category><category>水路运输/航运</category><category>Transportation/Logistics</category><category> Drones</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>海军</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>national</category><category>公安</category><category>armed forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>海军</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>marine transport</category><category> port</category><category>港口作业</category><category>aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category>货运</category><category>logistics</category><category> industrial goods</category><category>水运</category><category>shipping</category><category> transportation</category><category> drones </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ecuador Arrests Six Colombians in Slaying of Presidential Candidate]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Police say suspects are tied to drug trade; President Guillermo Lasso declares state of emergency as country grapples with drug violence <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124585"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3A297452-49E9-4885-AD64-0A664604940D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">距离大选不到两周，厄瓜多尔总统候选人费尔南多·维拉维森西奥在离开基多的竞选活动时被枪杀。这位腐败批评者表示，他收到了死亡威胁。照片：Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124585"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 10, 2023 8:12 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Six Colombians were arrested in connection with the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-presidential-candidate-who-had-denounced-gangs-is-assassinated-dad61aa5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">assassination of an Ecuadorean presidential candidate</a> in Quito, officials with Ecuador&#39;s Interior Ministry said, hours after President Guillermo Lasso declared a state of emergency to bring order to the country buffeted by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cocaine-trade-and-gang-violence-strike-hard-in-once-peaceful-ecuador-bad953c8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">drug-fueled violence</a> .</p><p> A high-ranking police official said the Colombians are part of a drug-trafficking criminal organization. He said some of the suspects had been arrested in the past in Ecuador and had also committed crimes in Colombia, where US officials say the cocaine trade is flourishing.</p><p> The official said the police were investigating two possible motives for the Wednesday killing of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72#phrase-person?ref=PERSON%7CVillavicencio%2C%20Fernando;onlineSignificance=prominent" class="icon none">Fernando Villavicencio</a> , but declined to provide additional information. Villavicencio, 59, was a former congressman and journalist who had railed against graft and pledged to battle drug gangs if elected president.</p><p> “They are part of organized crime,” the official said. “They are connected to drug trafficking and other crimes.”</p><p> The developments came after Lasso declared a 60-day, nationwide state of emergency that curtails civil liberties such as freedom of movement and the right to assembly. It takes force as several other candidates suspended their campaigns following the killing, the first time a presidential hopeful has been assassinated in Ecuador. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833924?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Police officers guard Ecuador&#39;s National Service of Legal Medicine and Forensic Sciences as a car transports the body of Ecuadorean presidential candidate Fernando Villavicencio.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯伦·托罗/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>拉索还宣布全国哀悼三天，并表示 8 月 20 日的选举将按计划进行。</p><p> “我们不会将权力和民主制度交给有组织犯罪，”拉索在电视评论中说。 “选举不会暂停。”</p><p> Villavicencio was killed after leaving a campaign event at a school in the capital, Quito.袭击发生在晚间高峰时段，地点靠近该市繁忙的金融中心。</p><p>距离投票仅 11 天，在支持者面前发生的枪击事件让厄瓜多尔人感到不安，他们已经在应对暴力犯罪激增的问题。贩毒团伙争夺可卡因贩运路线的控制权，在这个曾经相对和平的国家引发了流血事件。</p><p> “一切都那么令人困惑。太混乱了。人们不知道该怎么办。他们哭着，非常害怕。”摄影师迭戈·托雷斯 (Diego Torres) 和妻子在距离学校一个街区的地方散步时，听到了他所说的高威力步枪的射击声。 “这是另一个层面，更高级的犯罪行为。”</p><p>报道厄瓜多尔犯罪浪潮的托雷斯表示，他在枪声停止后赶到了现场。他说警方让他回去，因为他们发现了两枚没有爆炸的手榴弹。拉索说，袭击者在逃跑时投掷了一枚手榴弹，但并未爆炸，以分散当局的注意力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833925?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> One of the officers wounded in the attack on Fernando Villavicencio receives assistance.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: str/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Three police officers were injured in the attack on Villavicencio. In addition to those who were arrested, a suspected gunmen died of wounds sustained during an exchange of gunfire with police, officials said. The candidate had been using an armored vehicle during the campaign, however police said it had been left behind during a recent trip to the coastal city of Guayaquil.</p><p>对于枪击事件负责的说法相互矛盾。在 X（该网站以前称为 Twitter）上发布的一段视频中，全副武装的蒙面男子声称自己对这起杀戮负责，他们自称来自厄瓜多尔最大、最暴力的帮派之一“狼群”。后来，另一段视频中，未戴面具的男子也自称是狼队成员，称该团伙并未参与其中。 《华尔街日报》无法证实这些视频的真实性。</p><p> Villavicencio had recently said that he had received threats from another gang, known as the Choneros, which security experts say has ties to Mexico&#39;s Sinaloa cartel.</p><p> Villavicencio&#39;s death has drawn comparisons to the 1989 assassination of Colombian presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galán, who was killed by henchmen of drug kingpin Pablo Escobar after Galán campaigned on pledges to extradite drug traffickers to the US Colombian security officials were also involved and convicted in Galán&#39;s killing.</p><p>周四，这起谋杀案引起了华盛顿和北京的谴责。美国国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文称这是对厄瓜多尔民主的攻击。中国外交部表示，希望厄瓜多尔能够安全举行选举。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833230?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三，警方封锁了基多总统候选人费尔南多·比亚维森西奥被杀的学校周围地区。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：胡安·迭戈·黑山/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Antonio López, Villavicencio&#39;s campaign director, said he left the rally a couple of minutes before the candidate was killed. López recalled Villavicencio telling supporters at the rally that he was proud to be hated by criminals and that if elected, he would give gangs 90 days to hand in their weapons before he went after them.洛佩斯说，候选人最后一次收到死亡威胁是在八天前。</p><p>洛佩斯说：“民主被枪杀，反腐败斗争被削弱。” “他最大的斗争是打击毒品政治。”</p><p>最近几周，厄瓜多尔也有其他政客被杀。 7月，一名枪手在港口城市曼塔的市长奥古斯丁·英特里亚戈出席一场公共活动时刺杀了他。国民议会候选人 Rider Sánchez 上个月在沿海城市埃斯梅拉达斯被枪杀。路易斯·乔尼洛 (Luis Chonillo) 是犯罪猖獗的瓜亚基尔郊区的市长，他在五月份上任一天后就遭遇了一次暗杀。</p><p>随着有组织犯罪的猖獗，这场流血事件引发了人们对政治暴力在这个拥有 1800 万人口的安第斯国家蔓延的担忧。</p><p>华盛顿智库美洲对话组织的高级研究员迈克尔·希夫特表示：“哥伦比亚等其他国家的经验表明，有组织犯罪往往会演变为政治暴力。”</p><p> “当它这样做时，对民主制度和对政治制度的信心的影响可能是毁灭性的，”希夫特说。 “厄瓜多尔的转移速度快得惊人。”</p><p>如今，厄瓜多尔是拉丁美洲最危险的国家之一。据内政部称，自 2019 年以来，凶杀案增加了四倍，去年达到创纪录的 4,800 起，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/andes-turmoil-rattles-governments-spurs-migration-to-u-s-d8396753?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">导致移民激增</a>，主要是前往美国。</p><p>警方和安全专家表示， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colombias-acreage-of-coca-used-to-make-cocaine-surges-to-record-11666306614?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">邻国哥伦比亚创纪录的可卡因产量</a>以及墨西哥和阿尔巴尼亚贩毒集团支持的厄瓜多尔贩毒团伙之间的暴力事件引发了暴力浪潮。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833232?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周三，费尔南多·比亚维森西奥在基多遭到枪击后，他的亲属在诊所里等候。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: jose jacome/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Violence has mostly hit cities such as Guayaquil, as gangs fight for control of cocaine trafficking routes to maritime ports.警方和居民称，帮派执法者枪杀检察官和警察，将尸体吊在桥上，并招募儿童进行袭击。</p><p>由于选民要求加强安全，比亚维森西奥承诺打击贩毒团伙和有组织犯罪，他称这些犯罪团伙与厄瓜多尔政治精英关系密切。</p><p>他的政党表示，在曼塔市长被杀后，出于安全考虑，已讨论暂停他的竞选活动。比亚维森西奥的政党表示，他们坚决认为他们应该继续竞选。</p><p>比亚维森西奥当时表示：“当犯罪分子杀害公民和当局时，保持沉默和躲藏是一种懦弱和共谋的行为。” “我批准我的决定，继续进行日常斗争，直到我们击败黑手党。”</p><p>比亚维森西奥表示，他将在厄瓜多尔亚马逊地区为帮派头目建造一座最高安全级别的监狱，加强与美国的禁毒合作，并让军队负责用于运输可卡因的港口。他还承诺根除政府、警察和司法部门的腐败。</p><p>政治分析人士表示，比亚维森西奥是有机会在 8 月 20 日第一轮投票中获得第二名的候选人之一。民意调查显示，没有人能够在第一轮投票中获得足够的票数彻底赢得总统宝座。这种情况需要在十月份在两位前两名候选人之间进行决选。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833229?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统候选人费尔南多·比亚维森西奥 (Fernando Villavicencio) 在周三被枪杀前几分钟在一所学校的竞选活动中挥舞着国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在进入政坛之前，比亚维森西奥以记者身份而闻名，根据对政府腐败的详细调查，特别是在前总统拉斐尔·科雷亚执政期间，撰写了长篇文章和书籍。分析人士称，他的工作帮助科雷亚在 2020 年缺席被判腐败罪。</p><p>居住在比利时的科雷亚对比亚维森西奥的遇害表示哀悼，并向他的家人表示哀悼。</p><p> “厄瓜多尔已经成为一个失败的国家，”科雷亚在 X 上写道，“我对他的家人表示声援。”</p><p> 2014年，在人权组织称科雷亚政府镇压该国新闻自由的过程中，比亚维森西奥被指控诽谤，之后他躲藏在亚马逊地区。比亚维森西奥曾与一个土著部落一起生活过一段时间，后来逃到秘鲁寻求庇护。</p><p> 2017 年科雷亚政府结束后返回厄瓜多尔，比亚维森西奥当选为国民议会议员，并领导监督委员会。</p><p>他继续调查政府腐败，并就中国建造的基础设施项目的问题提出报告。他声称，以石油运输为担保的中国贷款已使该国损失数十亿美元，并助长了腐败。</p><p>美国陆军战争学院战略研究所研究中国与拉丁美洲关系的专家埃文·埃利斯表示，比亚维森西奥关于中国在厄瓜多尔日益增长的影响力的研究影响了他自己对北京在拉丁美洲不断扩大的作用的看法。</p><p> “对我来说，他是一个非常好的人，他情不自禁地说出了他所看到的真相，即使他有时会搬起石头砸自己的脚，树敌，”埃利斯说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——珍妮·卡罗莱纳·冈萨雷斯对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 11 Aug 2023 00:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecuador-declares-state-of-emergency-after-presidential-candidate-killed-6e639e72<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Crime/Legal Action</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>吉列尔莫·拉索</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>crime</category><category> legal action</category><category>贩毒</category><category>交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Iran Releases Four Americans From Evin Prison]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>德黑兰寻求冻结韩国数十亿美元的能源收入<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125422"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3EF0C42D-95E2-4D6C-A3B3-D34D9D232BB9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Firan-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Secretary of State Antony Blinken said sanctions against Iran will continue to be enforced. Photo: Cliff Owen/AP<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125422"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日晚上 7:54（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——美国和伊朗官员表示，伊朗已从臭名昭著的德黑兰监狱释放了五名美国人，但作为回报，伊朗也将释放五名囚犯以及数十亿美元的能源销售冻结收入。</p><p>周四，德黑兰释放了四名被软禁的美国人，打算让他们在未来几周内前往美国。第五名美国人已经被软禁，并将与其他四人一起离开伊朗。</p><p>白宫国家安全委员会在一份声明中表示：“在他们全部返回美国之前，我们不会休息。”官员们表示，在瑞士驻德黑兰大使馆和两个海湾阿拉伯国家的斡旋下<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-launches-quiet-diplomatic-push-with-iran-to-cool-tensions-2f45af3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，经过数月紧张但平静的外交，</a>事态取得了进展。</p><p>伊朗驻联合国代表团发言人表示，两国已同意“相互释放并赦免五名囚犯”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>该发言人在一份声明中表示：“将这些囚犯移出监狱标志着执行该协议的重要第一步。”</p><p>官方的伊斯兰共和国通讯社表示，超过100亿美元将从韩国和伊拉克的账户中提取，根据协议，在资金存入卡塔尔的伊朗账户之前，美国人不得离开伊朗。 A US official dismissed Iran&#39;s claim, saying that only the $6 billion in funds held in South Korea was under discussion.这位官员补充说，作为让这些美国人软禁的交换条件，美国没有释放任何伊朗囚犯。</p><p> “伊朗不会获得任何制裁减免，在任何情况下，我们将努力将美国人从伊朗带回家，伊朗自己的资金将被使用并转移到受限制的账户，这样这些钱只能用于人道主义目的……在我们的制裁下是允许的，”国务卿安东尼·布林肯周四告诉记者。 “我们将继续执行所有制裁措施。我们将继续打击伊朗在该地区及其他地区的破坏稳定活动，”他补充道。</p><p>伊朗官员一再将释放囚犯的可能性与动用在伊拉克用于交付天然气和石油的数十亿美元资金以及伊朗所说的在特朗普政府加强对韩国石油出口制裁后在韩国持有的 70 亿美元资金联系在一起。</p><p>知情人士表示，有关释放资金的讨论仍在进行中，但结果尚未确定。美国财政部正在探索如何将这些资金从无法使用的首尔受限账户转移到第三国，以便用于人道主义目的和美国制裁允许的其他贸易。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833471?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Siamak Namazi，2016 年 2 月发布的一张未注明日期的照片。这位美国人于 2015 年前往伊朗出差时被捕。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Republican presidential candidate <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">Mike Pence</a></p> criticized the agreement.<p></p><p> “伊朗现在将用这笔钱为俄罗斯生产无人机，并资助针对我们和以色列的恐怖主义，”副总统彭斯说，五人中至少有三人被监禁。 “同样扣押美国人质的中国和俄罗斯现在知道价格刚刚上涨。”</p><p>周四，其中一名人质 Siamak Namazi 的家人收到直接视觉确认，Namazi、Emad Shargi 和 Morad Tahbaz 已从 Evin 监狱获释，家人的律师 Jared Genser 说。他说，这三名男子和第四名未透露姓名的美国人已被带到监狱办公室，并被告知将被释放。他说，拜登政府周三下午已通知四名人质的家人，这是预料之中的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="641" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833474?width=639&amp;height=641" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">莫拉德·塔赫巴兹 (Morad Tahbaz) 于 2018 年入狱。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>自1979年伊斯兰革命后不久华盛顿和德黑兰断绝关系以来，瑞士一直代表美国在伊朗的外交利益，瑞士一直参与了谈判。据知情人士透露，瑞士驻德黑兰大使将可以完全接触被软禁的美国人。这位人士表示，卡塔尔和阿曼也协助推动了这些谈判。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-grants-furlough-to-american-prisoner-11664669202?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">纳马齐于 2015 年 10 月在前往伊朗出差时被捕</a>，罪名是与敌对政府合作。环保人士塔巴兹于 2018 年入狱，因间谍罪被判 10 年徒刑，已服刑 5 年。商人沙尔吉于 2018 年被捕，并于 2020 年未经审判以间谍罪被判处 10 年监禁。这三人都是美国和伊朗双重国籍。塔巴兹还拥有英国国籍。</p><p>知情人士称，另外两名被释放的人质，包括一名妇女，要求保密他们的身份。</p><p>最新的外交尝试代表了拜登政府的平衡之举，重点是缓解今年飙升的与德黑兰的紧张关系。伊朗<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-strikes-kill-six-in-ukraine-as-moscow-looks-to-undermine-kyivs-counteroffensive-177b0c2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为俄罗斯在乌克兰的战争提供了无人机</a>，推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-expands-nuclear-program-as-talks-to-revive-2015-deal-falter-11662569582?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">铀浓缩活动</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-tried-to-seize-two-oil-tankers-near-strait-of-hormuz-u-s-navy-says-4be301e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在波斯湾扣押了油轮</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=71B658F2-8859-45AF-95B9-DC8C297E36E2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Firan-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Iran attempted to seize two oil tankers near the Strait of Hormuz, the US Navy said last month. Video appears to show shots being fired at one of the oil tankers. Photo: US Department of Defense<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>官员们表示，在解放美国人的努力的同时，继续就恢复国际核协议进行谈判，该协议限制伊朗的核计划，以换取取消经济制裁。 The US withdrew from the pact under former President</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> .<p></p><p>随着总统选举的临近，拜登政府迫切希望避免将与伊朗的谈判推上政治议程的首位。然而，美国政府也注意到，鉴于伊朗的铀浓缩活动以及所谓的整个地区的破坏稳定活动，谈判有可能失败。</p><p>这些会谈也是在紧张的地区环境下进行的，美国正在向中东增派部队，以阻止和威慑霍尔木兹海峡针对国际商业油轮的袭击。美国还多次谴责和惩罚伊朗在乌克兰战争中向俄罗斯提供的援助。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Aresu Eqbali 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Vivian Salama： <a href="mailto:vivian.salama@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">vivian.salama@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 23:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-releases-four-americans-from-evin-prison-b396ee09<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Crime/Legal Action</category><category>国际关系</category><category>执法</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>监狱/囚犯</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>national</category><category>公安</category><category>crime</category><category> legal action</category><category>国际关系</category><category>执法</category><category>政治</category><category>监狱</category><category>囚犯</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A New Omicron Subvariant, Dubbed ‘Eris,’ Heralds Covid-19’s Resurgence]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我们对美国最常见的亚变体 EG.5 的了解<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833284?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">曼哈顿的一个弹出式 Covid-19 测试帐篷。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的加比·琼斯</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001124938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brianna-abbott" itemprop="url" rel="author">布莱恩娜·阿博特</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-kamp" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·坎普</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-s-hopkins" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·S·霍普金斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 3:18（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>现在还不要指望 Covid-19 被排除在外。</p><p>随着 Omicron 变种的另一个分支势头强劲，美国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Covid-19 感染人数</a>正在上升——在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-influenza-covid-19-tripledemic-this-winter-11667560508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">呼吸道疾病</a>通常会激增的秋季之前。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-do-we-actually-know-about-covid-19-not-enough-ec1dcafe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">该病毒的持续进化</a>提醒人们，尽管这种疾病的破坏性远不如以前，但 Covid-19 仍然对许多人来说是一个麻烦，对一些人来说仍然是一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/long-covid-symptoms-recovery-not-over-2e535790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">严重的风险</a>。废水中病毒浓度的不断上升和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/face-mask-mandates-fall-away-among-many-hospitals-doctors-6ecaa3e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">医院感染的</a>增加表明，Covid-19 仍然难以预测。</p><p>这种名为 EG.5 的新亚变体是另一个名为 XBB.1.9.2 的变体的后代，据世界卫生组织称，自 8 月 7 日以来，至少有 51 个国家报告了该变体，该组织将 EG.5 归类为本周感兴趣的一个变体。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833823?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> X（以前称为 Twitter）上的一些科学家将其非正式地称为“Eris”。世界卫生组织表示，与其他 Omicron 亚变体一样，EG.5 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/omicrons-trajectory-shows-challenge-of-maintaining-immune-defenses-11651829400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">具有免疫逃逸特性</a>，但没有迹象表明它更严重。</p><p>据美国疾病控制与预防中心称，截至 8 月 5 日，EG.5 预计约占美国病例的 17%，使其成为美国最流行的病毒版本。它是由十多个 Omicron 分支组成的动物园之一，估计至少占病例的 1%。</p><p>路易斯安那州卫生官员兼路易斯安那州卫生部医疗主任约瑟夫·坎特博士表示，由于没有足够的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-director-rochelle-walensky-politicization-science-9c291c7e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检测和测序数据</a>，疾病预防控制中心无法再对美国每个地区进行变异预测。</p><p> “我们预计 EG.5 将继续发挥重要作用，”坎特说。</p><p>卫生官员、疫苗制造商和医生正在为秋季疫苗接种活动做准备，这次活动将与之前的活动有所不同：疫苗将通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-plans-for-end-of-covid-19-shot-treatment-coverage-11660838418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">商业市场</a>而不是政府购买分发给药房和医生办公室。这些疫苗针对的是最近占主导地位的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/next-covid-shots-in-the-u-s-will-target-omicron-offshoot-xbb-1-5-35e212a0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">XBB.1.5 菌株，</a>符合美国食品和药物管理局今年早些时候制定的指示。</p><p>坎特说，针对 XBB.1.5 更新的助推器应该保留针对 EG.5 的良好保护，因为 Omicron 子变体是相似的。他说，很难预测这种保护会持续多久。</p><p>辉瑞首席执行官艾伯特·布尔拉 (Albert Bourla) 本月表示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PFE" class="company-name">辉瑞</a>预计其新疫苗将于本月获得批准，疫苗接种可能于 9 月开始。辉瑞公司发言人表示，预计该增强剂能够对抗 EG.5，因为它是 Omicron 的一个分支，但正在进行实验室测试以确保这一点。辉瑞和合作伙伴<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BNTX" class="company-name">BioNTech</a>在 6 月份的会议上向 FDA 顾问介绍了如何更新疫苗的动物测试。</p><p> FDA 不太可能要求制造商生产针对 EG.5 的疫苗，因为供应无法及时准备好以供秋季活动使用。辉瑞和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MRNA" class="company-name">Moderna</a>至少需要三个月的时间才能针对 Covid-19 进行 mRNA 注射。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>发言人表示，Moderna 的更新疫苗供应充足，正在等待 FDA 批准分配剂量。他说，初步测试表明该镜头对 EG.5 有效，更多测试正在进行中。</p><p>一位发言人表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVAX" class="">Novavax</a>的 Covid-19 疫苗使用了不同的技术，该公司正在向监管机构提交数据以授权其加强剂，并预计在 9 月份获得许可并发货。</p><p>是否立即接受加强注射或等待新的加强注射<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-you-never-got-covid-19-thank-your-genes-d61c7507?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取决于某人的健康状况和风险</a>， <strong>&nbsp;</strong>威尔康奈尔医学院微生物学和免疫学教授约翰摩尔博士说。他说，患有已有疾病或免疫系统受损的人以及未接种疫苗的人仍然面临高风险。</p><p> “如果您和您的医生认为您现在需要加强注射，请立即注射，”摩尔说。 “这非常有个性。没有一个简单的桶可以容纳每个美国人。”</p><p>去年，RSV 早期严重激增以及流感导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rsv-hospitalizations-babies-young-children-11668080478?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">儿科医院不堪重负</a>，卫生官员正在为其他呼吸道感染的增加做好准备。 FDA 已批准首款<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-pfizer-rsv-vaccine-rolls-out-into-headwinds-of-hesitancy-74c8aece?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于 60 岁及以上成年人的</a>RSV 疫苗以及一种<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于保护婴儿的新药</a>。</p><p> “我们正在进入一个我们并不真正知道这些病毒将如何相互作用的季节，”康涅狄格州公共卫生部专员马尼沙·朱萨尼博士说。</p><p>美国不再像以前那样密切跟踪 Covid-19 感染和住院情况。长期以来，感染情况一直难以记录，因为人们不再在向州卫生当局提供数据的设施中接受检测。医院还取消了对所有患者的常规检测。</p><p>几周来，医院内的 Covid-19 病例一直呈上升趋势。 CDC 表示，截至 7 月底的最新一周内，有 9,056 人因 Covid-19 入院，增长了 12.5%。许多患者因其他原因住院，而不是因为感染，但医院的阳性检测可以反映出社区感染流行率的增加。</p><p> Covid-19 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-million-deaths-the-hole-the-pandemic-made-in-u-s-society-11643662159?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都会导致新的死亡病例</a>，尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-u-s-covid-19-death-toll-is-still-rising-93b2b12a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">远未达到大流行初期的峰值</a>。最近的死亡证明数据显示，美国平均每天有不到 100 例 Covid-19 死亡病例。 2021 年 1 月，一周内每天死亡人数达到历史最高值约 3,700 人。</p><p>写信给 Brianna Abbott（ <a href="mailto:brianna.abbott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">brianna.abbott@wsj.com</a> ）、Jon Kamp（ <a href="mailto:Jon.Kamp@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Jon.Kamp@wsj.com</a> ）和 Jared S. Hopkins（ <a href="mailto:jared.hopkins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.hopkins@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 19:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eg5-eris-new-covid-19-variant-fa3cc260<author><![CDATA[Brianna AbbottJon KampJared S. Hopkins]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>Vaccines</category><category>纺织品</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>服装/纺织品</category><category>消费品</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category> Health</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>Medical Conditions</category><category> Outbreaks/Epidemics</category><category> Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>莫德纳</category><category>信使核糖核酸</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category> health</category><category>免疫接种</category><category>medical conditions</category><category> outbreaks</category><category> epidemics</category><category> novel coronaviruses</category><category> infectious diseases</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>药品</category><category>疫苗</category><category>纺织品</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>衣服</category><category>消费品</category><category>专门药物</category><category>药物</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russian Tech Giant’s Co-Founder Speaks Out Against Ukraine War]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Former Yandex chief executive Arkady Volozh condemns the invasion as barbaric <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125808"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="615" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833599?width=860&amp;height=615" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Arkady Volozh, a founder of Russia&#39;s Yandex, moved to Israel in 2014.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dmitry Astakhov/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125808"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-m-simmons" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ann M. Simmons</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 10, 2023 2:42 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-tech-giants-co-founder-speaks-out-against-ukraine-war-686f9cf1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The co-founder of Russian tech giant Yandex condemned what he described as Russia&#39;s barbaric <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-uses-small-unit-tactics-to-retake-captured-territory-from-russia-d9ef32a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">war in Ukraine</a> , in some of the most pointed criticism so far from a leader of the country&#39;s business community.</p><p> Arkady Volozh, the company&#39;s former chief executive, lamented the destruction being leveled upon Russia&#39;s smaller neighbor in what Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> calls a special military operation.</p><p> “I am categorically against it,” Volozh said Thursday. “I am horrified about the fate of people in Ukraine—many of them my personal friends and relatives—whose houses are being bombed every day.”</p><p> He added that although he moved to Israel in 2014, “I have to take my share of responsibility for the country&#39;s actions.”</p><p> Yandex runs Russia&#39;s largest search engine and ride-hailing service and is often referred to as Russia&#39;s Google. Company representatives didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment on Volozh&#39;s statement condemning the war. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833603?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Yandex runs Russia&#39;s largest search engine and ride-hailing service.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sergei Bobylev/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Russia has increasingly sought <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-court-sentences-kremlin-critic-vladimir-kara-murza-to-25-years-for-treason-13c8526c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to repress those who criticize the war</a> and how the Kremlin&#39;s army is executing it. Several journalists, activists, dissidents and ordinary Russians have been detained, fined or saddled with lengthy prison sentences after being accused of discrediting Russia&#39;s military.</p><p> Volozh&#39;s comments followed a backlash he faced earlier this week when he removed Russia from his bio on a personal website, describing himself as a “Kazakhstan-born, Israeli tech entrepreneur.” Critics accused him of trying to dissociate himself with Russia.</p><p> Pro-Putin Russian television personality, Vladimir Solovyov, accused Volozh and other wealthy Russian businessmen who have left the country and sought to distance themselves from Russia of exploiting the nation.</p><p> “Listen you fat cats, on whom did you earn your money,” he said on a live show earlier this week.</p><p> Most of Russia&#39;s wealthy elite have refrained from publicly denouncing Putin or his actions in Ukraine. Volozh joins a limited cadre of prominent businessmen who have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/roman-abramovich-ukraine-russia-peace-sanctions-11674572583?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">spoken out against the war</a> , including Roman Abramovich, former owner of Chelsea Premier League football club; aluminum magnate Oleg Deripaska and Mikhail Fridman,</p> a co-founder of Alfa-Group, a multinational Russian conglomerate. All have been hit with European sanctions over the war.<p></p><p> In June 2022, the European Union sanctioned Volozh, saying the company was “responsible for promoting state media and narratives in its search results, and deranking and removing content critical of the Kremlin.”</p><p> He stepped down from his role as CEO. Yandex&#39;s board of directors defended Volozh, saying in a statement at that time that the sanctions were based on an inaccurate understanding of what Yandex does.</p><p> “In our minds, when we founded it, we weren&#39;t only creating a technology company,” Volozh said Thursday. “We were helping to create a new Russia—open, progressive, integrated into the global economy, and able to bring value to the world beyond natural resources.”</p><p> Last year, Yandex <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-yandex-sells-assets-to-state-backed-firm-as-kremlin-tightens-grip-on-internet-11661284203?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sold its media interests</a> to a state-backed company, a move which essentially allowed the Kremlin to deepen its control over the Russian internet.</p><p> Some antiwar commentators criticized Volozh for not speaking out earlier. In his statement, he said there were many reasons he had remained silent, but didn&#39;t explain further.</p><p> “While there will anyway be questions about the timing of my statement today, there should be no questions about its essence,” he said. “I am against the war.”</p><p> Write to Ann M. Simmons at <a href="mailto:ann.simmons@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ann.simmons@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 18:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-tech-giants-co-founder-speaks-out-against-ukraine-war-686f9cf1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-tech-giants-co-founder-speaks-out-against-ukraine-war-686f9cf1<author><![CDATA[Ann M. Simmons]]></author><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>Online Service Providers</category><category> Technology</category><category> Management</category><category> Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Senior Level Management</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Arkady Volozh</category><category> management</category><category> corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category> senior level management</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>national</category><category>公安</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>online service providers</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Is Happening in Niger? What to Know About the Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国西非反恐盟友民选总统下台引发军事干预威胁<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829069/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 10 日下午 1:26（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> 7 月 26 日，尼日尔精锐总统卫队官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了西非国家当选总统</a>穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并宣布自己为该国新领导人。这次政变令美国和欧洲政府感到震惊，这些国家一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-russia-africa-86cf1454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与巴祖姆和尼日尔军队密切合作</a>，打击非洲萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>尼日尔的一些西非邻国（主要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和欧洲结盟</a>）威胁要使用武力恢复巴祖姆的地位。其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯结盟的</a>国家则表示，他们将捍卫尼日尔的新军政府。</p><h3>美国和欧洲政府为何担心尼日尔政变？</h3><p>尼日尔一直是美国和欧洲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">打击基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子</a>的中心，这些武装分子近年来在撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区萨赫勒地区杀害了数千人。在马里和布基纳法索军方领导的政府驱逐了一直在那里与伊斯兰叛乱分子作战的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">法国和其他西方军队</a>后，尼日尔变得更加重要。美国已花费约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，配备从帐篷、收音机到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。美国在尼日尔驻有约 1,100 名士兵，他们训练当地特种部队并为他们执行任务提供建议。法国在尼日尔驻有大约 1,500 名士兵。</p><p>欧盟还依赖世界上最贫穷国家之一的尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-considers-substantial-fund-for-africa-to-deal-with-migrants-1440871414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来阻止非洲移民</a>进入利比亚并从那里进入欧盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="819" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828956?width=1260&amp;height=819" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">政变支持者在尼亚美示威期间悬挂俄罗斯国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>什么是西共体？它能扭转政变吗？</h3><p> 7月30日，西非国家经济共同体（目前由尼日利亚领导的政治和经济组织）的11个国家给尼日尔军政府7天的时间恢复巴祖姆的权力，并威胁如果不这样做就会进行武装干预。他们还对尼日尔实施了一系列严厉的金融和贸易制裁，希望迫使军政府做出让步。</p><p>作为回应，马里和布基纳法索的政变也受到西非经共体的谴责，它们警告说，他们将把对尼日尔的武装干预视为宣战，并将保卫尼亚美军政府。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-u-s-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">尼日尔军事领导人</a>无视西非经共体的最后通牒，并拒绝了西非经共体代表团多次试图通过谈判寻求恢复该国文官政府的途径。</p><p> 8月10日，尼日利亚总统博拉·蒂努布在西非经共体领导人第二次峰会后警告说，如果其他向军政府施压的手段失败，武装干预仍然是可能的。蒂努布说：“我们不会放弃任何选择，包括使用武力作为最后手段。” “如果我们不这样做，没有人会为我们做这件事。”</p><p>在峰会上，西非经共体还下令部署一支“待命部队”，但没有提供该部队的组成或部署地点和时间的详细信息。</p><p>分析人士警告说，干预可能会将迄今为止的不流血政变变成导致许多平民死亡的地区冲突。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828965?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲和美国公民从尼日尔撤离后抵达罗马附近的机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>美国如何回应？</h3><p>拜登总统和国务卿安东尼·布林肯呼吁释放巴祖姆并保护尼日尔的民主。 8月4日，美国政府效仿欧洲各国政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-pause-some-financial-aid-to-niger-as-country-reels-from-coup-7252caa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">暂停了对尼日尔的部分财政援助，</a>以向军政府施加压力。尼日尔近一半的预算来自外国援助，其中大部分来自西方政府。</p><p>然而，美国官员一直小心翼翼地避免将军方的行动称为政变，这一名称将引发美国法律<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对军事援助的限制</a>。国防部表示，没有计划将军事人员或装备撤出尼日尔，并支持通过外交途径解决局势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2AE037D3-6705-43B5-828C-C117387FADDD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔上周发生政变后，欧洲各国政府和美国下令从尼日尔撤离本国公民。军政府领导人表示，军方不会屈服于压力，要求让被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆复职。照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>8 月 7 日，代理副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰 (Victoria Nuland) 前往尼日尔，会见了军政府领导人之一尼日尔将军。</p>穆萨·萨拉乌·巴尔穆 (Moussa Salaou Barmou) 和他的顾问们进行了两个多小时的讨论。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-trained-general-65b5ecd6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">巴尔穆曾在尼日尔与美国特种部队密切合作</a>。<p></p><p> “我希望他们保持外交大门敞开。我们提出了这个建议……他们对于如何推进有自己的想法，”纽兰告诉记者。 “他们的想法不符合宪法，如果他们走这条路，我们的关系就会很困难。但我们给了他们一些继续谈话的选择，我们希望他们接受我们的建议。”</p><p>她说，她多次要求与巴祖姆会面，但都被拒绝了。</p><p>美国国务院已下令<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">撤离美国驻尼亚美大使馆的所有非必要人员</a>以及美国大使馆工作人员的家属。与法国不同的是，美国尚未从尼日尔全面撤离美国公民。法国已向尼日尔派遣了多架撤侨航班，并表示已帮助约 40 名美国公民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828970?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆与美国和欧洲政府密切合作，打击伊斯兰激进分子。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社/媒体库</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>奥马尔·查尼将军是谁？</h3><p>尊敬的奥马尔·查尼将军，</p>有时也被称为阿卜杜拉哈曼 (Abdourahamane)，是发动反对巴祖姆起义的总统卫队首领。他现在作为尼日尔自封的领导人领导军政府。据熟悉尼日尔局势的人士透露，巴祖姆一直在考虑是否解雇蒂亚尼，这是政变的触发因素之一。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829050?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">军政府首脑、尼日尔自称领导人奥马尔·查尼将军率领总统卫队发动了政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ORTN/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>尼日尔军政府想要什么？</h3><p>奇亚尼和其他军政府成员都提到了尼日尔不断恶化的安全局势。然而，根据非营利性武装冲突地点和事件数据项目的数据，2023 年上半年，尼日尔针对平民的袭击减少了 49%，而造成的死亡人数与前六个月相比下降了 16%。 Acled 数据显示，去年尼日尔发生了 114 起圣战组织袭击事件。</p><p>军政府尚未就其与莫斯科的关系发表任何公开声明，但其早期行动表明它可能会脱离西方。 8月3日晚，它宣布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-end-military-cooperation-with-france-deepening-concerns-over-anti-western-turn-e7fae57e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">终止与法国的军事合作</a>，包括授权法国军队留在该国。法国外交部表示，不承认军政府的权威，也没有撤军计划。奇亚尼还派遣一名副手前往马里与该国亲俄罗斯领导人进行会谈。</p><h3>俄罗斯对尼日尔政变持何立场？</h3><p>俄罗斯政府呼吁尼日尔恢复宪法秩序，并警告不要进行武装干预。叶夫根尼·普里戈津（Yevgeny Prigozhin）的准军事瓦格纳集团已经在马里拥有战士，他赞扬了这次政变，并向尼亚美军政府提供了他的雇佣军服务。</p><p>法国外交部长指责俄罗斯的虚假信息导致了针对其大使馆的支持政变的抗议活动。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —William Mauldin 和 Vivian Salama 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟 (Gabriele Steinhauser)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 10 Aug 2023 17:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-Russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-Russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>Crime/Legal Action</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Terrorism</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器